snippet.textDisplay: I recently found your channel and subscribed, But I wanted to point out something I've heard in a lot of your videos. When you're driving them around with no coolant and/or radiator and say it didn't overheat. You can't tell if an engine is overheating if you don't have coolant in it. The Temp Sensor works by detecting the temperature of the coolant itself. So without the coolant dispersing the heat and equalizing the different temperature zones of the block and heads the Temp sensor cant give you an accurate temperature reading. Aluminum is sensative to tempatures and even worse when you have blocks/heads and other components comprised of different metals that heat/expand, cool/shrink at different rates. The potential damage may not present itself right away but shorten the life of an engine. Cause compression leaks, coolant or oil sooner than normal.
